@node Catalog description
@chapter Catalog description files
@cindex Catalog description
@cindex .cd
A catalog description file contains four kinds of lines.

@table @strong
@item Comment lines
Any line beginning with a semicolon is assumed to be a comment line,
hence ignored. (The string lines below are an exception. These may begin
with a semicolon.)

@item Command lines
Any line beginning with a '#' (with the same exception as above) are
assumed to be command lines. Possible commands are:
@table @code
@item #language <str>
gives the programs default language, the language of the strings in the
catalog description. Default is @samp{#language english}.
@item #version <num>
gives the version number of catalogs to be opened. Note that this number
must match exact and not be same or higher as in @cite{Exec/OpenLibrary}.
An exception is the number 0, which accepts any catalog. Default is
@samp{#version 0}. See @code{Locale/OpenCatalog} for further information
on catalog language and version.
@item #lengthbytes <num>
Instructs FlexCat to put the given number of bytes before a string containing
its length. The length is the number of bytes in the string without length
bytes and a trailing @samp{NUL} byte. (Catalog files and hence catalog
strings will have a trailing @samp{NUL} byte. This is not always true for
the default strings, depending on the source description file.)
@samp{<num>} must be between 0 and sizeof(long)=4, Default is
@samp{#lengthbytes 0}.
@item #basename <str>
Sets the basename of the source description. @xref{Source description}.
This overwrites the basename from the command line argument CDFILE.
@xref{Program start}.
@end table
Commands are case insensitive.
@item Description lines
declare a string. They look like @samp{IDSTR (id/minlen/maxlen)} where
@samp{IDSTR} is a identifier (a string consisting of the characters
a-z,A-Z and 0-9), @samp{id} is a unique number (from now on called ID),
@samp{minlen} and @samp{maxlen}
are the strings minimum and maximum length, respectively. The latter three
may be missing (but not the characters @samp{(//)}!) in which case FlexCat
chooses a number and makes no restrictions on the string length.
Better don't use the ID's, if you don't need. The lines following are the
@item String lines
@cindex Control characters
@cindex Ascii-Code
containing the string itself and nothing else. These may contain certain
control characters beginning with a backslash:
@table @samp
@item \b
Backspace (Ascii 8)
@item \c
Control Sequence Introducer (Ascii 155)
@item \e
Escape (Ascii 27)
@item \f
Form Feed (Ascii 12)
@item \g
Display beep (Ascii 7)
@item \n
Line Feed, newline (Ascii 10)
@item \r
Carriage Return (Ascii 13)
@item \t
Tab (Ascii 9)
@item \v
Vertical tab (Ascii 11)
@item \)
The trailing bracket which is possibly needed as part of a @samp{(..)}
sequence, see @ref{Source description}.
@item \\
The backslash itself
@item \xHH
The character given by the ascii code @samp{HH}, where @samp{HH} are hex
digits.
@item \OOO
The character given by the ascii code @samp{OOO}, where @samp{OOO} are octal
digits.
@end table
Finally a single backslash at the end of the line causes concatening the
following line. This makes it possible to use strings of any length, FlexCat
makes no assumptions on string length.
@end table

A string is hence given by a description line and the following string line.
Let's see an example:
@example
    msgHello (/4/)
    Hello, this is english!\n
@end example
@noindent
@cindex FlexCat.cd
The ID is missing here, so FlexCat chooses a suitable number. The number 4
instructs FlexCat, that the following string must not have less than four
characters and it may be of any length. See the file @file{FlexCat.cd} for
a further example.



