@node Catalog translation
@chapter Catalog translation files
@cindex Catalog translation
@cindex .ct
Catalog translation files are very similar to catalog descriptions, except
for other commands and having no informations on string ID and length.
(These are taken from the catalog description.) Any string from the
catalog description must be present (However, FlexCat omits writing
strings into the catalog which are identical to the default string.)
and no additional identifiers may occur. This is easy assured by using
FlexCat to create new catalog translation files. @xref{Overview}.

The commands allowed in catalog translations are:
@table @code
@item ##version <str>
Gives the catalog version as AmigaDOS version string. Example:
@example
    @samp{##version $VER: FlexCat.ct 8.3 (06.03.98)}
@end example
The version number of this catalog is 8. Hence the catalog descriptions
version number must be 0 or 8.

You may replace the date string @samp{27.09.93} with special keyword
@samp{$TODAY}.  While creating catalog, @samp{$TODAY} will be replaced by current
date (note, only 1st occurance of @samp{$TODAY} in @samp{$VER} string will be processed).
If you want your version strings to always be recent type i.e.:
@example
    @samp{$VER: FlexCat.ct 2.2 ($TODAY)}
@end example

Please note, that from FlexCat 2.6 on, the date is automatically updated.
This way the you know, if the compiled catalog is up-to-date in relation
to a catalog translation.
Furthermore you can now have a correct version string in the .ct file,
denoting that is is a .ct file. FlexCat automatically turns the ".ct"
into  ".catalog" when creating the catalog file.

@item ##rcsid $Date$ $Revision$ $Id$
can be used in conjunction with a revision control system instead
of ##version. @samp{<date>} is the date in the form @samp{yy/mm/dd},
@samp{time} is the time (ignored), @samp{<rev>} the revision and
@samp{<name>} the name to be used in the version string.

@item ##name <name>
is present for CatComp compatibility only. It replaces the
@samp{<name>} argument in the @code{##rcsid} command.

@item ##language <str>
The catalogs language. Of course this should be another language than the
catalog descriptions language. The @samp{##language} and @samp{##version}
commands must be present in a catalog translation.
@item ##codeset <num>
Currently not used, must be 0. This is the default value.
@item ## chunk <ID> <string>
Adds a chunk ID to the catalog which consists if the given <string>.
Usually one uses this to add comments to the catalog.
@example
    ## chunk AUTH German catalog translation by Jochen Wiedmann
@end example
@end table

@cindex Deutsch.ct
The string from above looks like this in the catalog translation:
@example
    msgHello
    Hallo, dies ist deutsch!\n
@end example
@noindent
See @file{Deutsch.ct} as further example of a catalog translation.



