@node Source description
@chapter Source description files
@cindex Source description
@cindex .sd
This is the special part of FlexCat. Until now there is nothing that
CatComp, KitCat and others don't offer too. The created source should make
it easy, to use the catalogs without losing flexibility. Any programming
language should be possible and any requirements should be satisfyable.
This seems like a contradiction, but FlexCat's solution are the source
description files containing a template of the source to be created. These
are editable as the catalog description and translation files are,
hence FlexCat can create any code.

The source descriptions are searched for certain symbols which are replaced
by certain values. Possible symbols are the backslash characters from
above and additionally sequences beginning with a @samp{%}. (This is well
known for C programmers.)
@table @samp
@item %b
is the base name of the catalog description. @xref{Program start}.
@item %v
is the version number of the catalog description. Don't mix this up with
the catalog version string from the catalog translation.
@item %l
is the catalog descriptions language. Please note, that this is inserted
as a string. See @samp{%s} below.
below.
@item %n
is the number of strings in the catalog description.
@item %%
is the character @samp{%} itself.
@end table

But the most important thing are the following seqences. These represent
the catalog strings in different ways. Lines containing one or more of these
symbols are repeated for any String.

@table @samp

@item %i
is the identifier from the catalog description.

@item %nd
@itemx %nx
@itemx %nc
is the strings ID in decimal, hexadecimal or octal characters, respectively.
The number @samp{n} tells FlexCat, how many characters the ID should use
(the string will be filled with Zeros at the left). You may omit @samp{n}:
In this case the ID will take just the number of characters it needs.

@item %e
is the number of this string. Counting begins with 0.

@item %s
is the string itself; this will be inserted in a way depending on the
programming language and can be controlled using the commands
@samp{##stringtype} and @samp{##shortstrings}.

@item %na
is the string's ID. The difference between @samp{%na} and e.g. @samp{%nx} is that
the @samp{%na} produces string's ID @strong{parted} to single bytes:
@example
  @samp{%2a} in source descriptor will produce @samp{\x00\0x20}
@end example
You may omit @samp{n}. In this case the ID will take 4 bytes.

@item %nt
is the string's len. Please note, that the result value is always @strong{even}.

@item %z
this item should be used together with @samp{%nt}. Because @samp{%nt} always returns
even value having desriptor line like:
@example 
static const char Block[] =
@{
     "%2a" "%2t" %s "%z"
@};
@end example
may lead to problems, especially while parsing such table, because @samp{%2t}
might be even while real string's @samp{%s} lenght may be odd! So while parsing
you read or skip one byte too much (I guess consequences are known). To avoid
such problems @samp{%z} was introduced. FlexCat replaces it with as many bytes
(@samp{\x00}) as many string's lenght lacks to even. So if string is 3 bytes
long @samp{%nt} returns @samp{4} and @samp{%z} adds one @samp{\x00}

@item %(...)
inserts the text between the brackets for any string except the last.
This is probably needed in Arrays, if the array entries should be separated
by commas, but the last entry must not be followed by a comma. You can
use @samp{%(,)} in that case. Note that within the brackets there is no
replacing of @samp{%} sequences. Backslash sequences, however, are still
allowed.

@end table

The control sequences @samp{%l} and @samp{%s} create strings. But how strings
look depends on the program language. That's why the source description
allows command lines similar to the catalog translation. These must begin
with the first character of the line and any command must have its own line.
Possible commands are:
@table @code
@item ##shortstrings
makes longer strings to be splitted on different lines. This is probably
not always possible or not implemented into FlexCat and hence the default
is to create one, probably very long string.
@item ##stringtype <type>
Tells FlexCat how strings should look like. Possible types are
@table @strong
@item None
No additional characters are created. An image of the string is inserted
and nothing else. No output of binary characters (the backslash sequences)
is possible.
@item C
creates strings according to C. The strings are preceded and followed by
the character @samp{"}. Strings are splitted using the sequences
@samp{"\} at the end of the line and @samp{"} at the beginning of the
new line. (The backslash is needed in macros.) Binary characters are
inserted using @samp{\OOO}. @xref{C}.
@item Oberon
is like string type C, except for the trailing backslash at the end of the
line. @xref{Oberon}. This string type is recommended for Modula-2, too.
@item Assembler
Strings are created using @samp{dc.b}. Readable ascii characters are preceded
and followed by the character @samp{'}, binary characters are inserted as
@samp{$XX}. @xref{Assembler}.
@item E
Strings are preceded and followed by the character @samp{'}. A @samp{+}
concatenates strings which are spread on different lines. Binary characters
are inserted like in C.
@end table
@end table

Let's look at an excerpt from the file @file{C_h.sd} creating an include
file for the programming language C.
@example
##stringtype C
##shortstrings

#ifndef %b_CAT_H    /*  Assure that this is read only once. */
#define %b_CAT_H


/*  Get other include files     */
#include <exec/types.h>
#include <libraries/locale.h>


/*  Prototypes  */
extern void Open%bCatalog(struct Locale *, STRPTR);
extern void Close%bCatalog(void);
extern STRPTR Get%bString(LONG);

/*  Definitions of the identifiers and their ID's           */
/*  This line will be repeated for any string.              */
#define %i %d

#endif
@end example

For the search path that is used for source descriptions see
@xref{Program start}.




