@node Using FlexCat source
@chapter Including FlexCat source in own programs
@cindex Using FlexCat source
@cindex FlexCat source
Of course this depends on what source is created and hence on the
source description. What we are talking here about are the source description
files distributed with FlexCat. @xref{Source description}.

All source descriptions should allow using the program without
@code{locale.library}. However, a global variable called @samp{LocaleBase}
(@samp{_LocaleBase} for assembler) must be present and initialized with
NULL or by a call to @cite{Exec/OpenLibrary}. No localizing is possible in
the former case except when using the source description @file{C_c_V20.sd}.
This allows localizing on 2.0 by repacing the @code{locale.library} with the
@code{iffparse.library}. (A variable @samp{IFFParseBase} has to be present
for this and initialized like @samp{LocaleBase}.) @xref{C}.
The programmer does not need knowledge of these libraries except when
creating own source descriptions.

There are three functions and calling them is rather simple.
@deffn {} OpenCatalog (locale, language)
This function possibly opens a catalog. The argument @code{locale} is a
pointer to a Locale structure amd @code{language} is a string containing
the name of the language that should be opened. In most cases these should
both be @samp{NULL} or @samp{NIL}, respectively, because the user's defaults
are overwritten otherwise. See @cite{Locale.OpenCatalog} for details.

Non object oriented languages (C, Assembler, Modula) usually call these
function @code{OpenXXXCatalog}, where XXX is the base name of the application:
This allows to use different catalogs in the same program.

If the user has @samp{Deutsch} and @samp{Français} as default languages
and the programs base name is @samp{XXX} this looks for the following files:
@example
    @file{PROGDIR:Catalogs/Deutsch/XXX.catalog}
    @file{LOCALE:Catalogs/Deutsch/XXX.catalog}
    @file{PROGDIR:Catalogs/Français/XXX.catalog}
    @file{LOCALE:Catalogs/Français/XXX.catalog}
@end example
@noindent
where @file{PROGDIR:} is the programs current directory. (The order of
@file{PROGDIR:} and @file{LOCALE:} can get changed in order to suppress a
requester like @samp{Insert volume YYY}.

OpenCatalog is of type void (a procedure for Pascal programmers) and hence
gives no result.
@end deffn

@deffn {} GetString (ID)
Gives a pointer to the string with the given ID from the catalog description.
Of course these strings are owned by @code{locale.library} and must not be
modified.

An example might be useful. Take the string from the catalog description
example, which was called @code{msgHello}. The source descriptions
declare a constant @samp{msgHello} representing the ID. This could be
printed in C using
@example
    printf("%s\n", GetString(msgHello));
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn {} CloseCatalog (void)
This function frees the catalog (that is the allocated RAM) before
terminating the program. You can call this function at any time even before
OpenCatalog is called.
@end deffn

